From: tawc
Origin: own

Make Kumquat::run robust to two client-lifecycle events that
upstream's loop mishandles, both of which we hit constantly.

1. Per-client backend error. Upstream
   `gpu_conn.process_command(...)?` propagates per-request failures
   to Kumquat::run, where they short-circuit the whole event loop
   and exit main(). A guest hitting an unimplemented backend path
   (e.g. gfxstream's PLATFORM_AHB export, which our
   01-drop-nativewindow-dep.patch surfaces as InvalidResourceId)
   takes the daemon with it. We absorb the error into "drop just
   this connection" plus an eprintln, so the failing client gets
   EOF on its socket and the next reconnect / sibling chroot keeps
   working. The connection's resources die through
   `o.remove_entry()` → KumquatGpuConnection::Drop, same path as a
   normal disconnect.

2. Peer EOF / busy spin. The bool returned from process_command is
   true iff recv() returned 0 bytes — `kumquat_stream.rs` pushes
   `OkNoData` and `kumquat_gpu/mod.rs` sets the flag. Upstream's
       hung_up = !peer_eof && event.hung_up;
   never fires on the common case "peer closed cleanly after
   draining": `!peer_eof` flips to false and we don't drop. The
   closed FD then stays in wait_ctx; epoll is level-triggered with
   `EventFlags::IN` registered (mesa3d/.../linux/wait_context.rs)
   and EPOLLHUP/EPOLLIN are sticky on a closed peer, so wait()
   returns immediately every iteration and Kumquat::run busy-spins
   at 100% CPU per leaked connection. Tawc hit this every time a
   chroot-side gfxstream-vk client process exited.

   Fix the condition to drop on peer EOF, and add a sibling
   `else if event.hung_up` arm so half-closed wakeups with no
   readable data are still cleaned out of wait_ctx (a defensive
   guard — current epoll/SEQPACKET semantics report EPOLLIN
   alongside EPOLLHUP, but the logic is one line and we'd rather
   not depend on that).

Local rename `no_more_data → peer_eof` is just clarity — the bool
really does mean "peer hit EOF", not "we drained the buffer for
now". The old name is what made upstream's condition look
plausible at a glance.

